    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab> 
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><persName><name>mia</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Tertia">Tertia</name></persName> 
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><persName><name>o</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Rufus">Rufo</name></persName> fecit.
            </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation">
                <p>"[---]mia Tertia…made this for…Rufus"</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The AAR identifies the piece as a <hi rend="italic">columbarium</hi> fragment. While this is perhaps
                    generous given the limited preservation of the text, the orthography certainly
                    points to an imperial dating. If it is indeed <hi rend="italic">columbarium</hi>, then the date would
                    most likely be no later than the 120s CE. Side B is possibly the verso, given
                    the fact that it seems to be the more rounded side, and marble workers often
                    rounded the new side which would be flush to the wall. Additionally, Di Stefano
                    Manzella notes that for the imperial period, the higher quality orthography is
                    usually the older side the quality of the orthography of side B seems greater,
                    with its more consistent and well-defined strokes.</p></div>
            

